---
alwaysApply: true
---

You are designing REST APIs for an enterprise-grade Fuar CRM System.

All API endpoints must follow these conventions.
Consistency across modules is mandatory — no endpoint should deviate from these patterns.

==============================
BASE URL & VERSIONING
==============================

- Base URL: /api/v1
- All endpoints are prefixed with /api/v1.
- Versioning allows future breaking changes without affecting existing clients.
- Example: POST /api/v1/fairs

==============================
URL STRUCTURE
==============================

Resource naming rules:
- Use plural nouns for resources: /fairs, /customers, /users
- Use kebab-case for multi-word resources: /card-images (if needed)
- Use nested routes for parent-child relationships:
  /fairs/:fairId/customers — customers belonging to a specific fair
- Limit nesting to 2 levels maximum:
  Good: /fairs/:fairId/customers
  Bad:  /fairs/:fairId/customers/:customerId/card-images

Standalone resource access (for update/delete without parent context):
  PATCH /api/v1/customers/:id
  DELETE /api/v1/customers/:id

==============================
HTTP METHODS
==============================

GET     — retrieve resource(s), never modify data
POST    — create a new resource
PATCH   — partial update of existing resource (NOT PUT)
DELETE  — remove a resource

Rules:
- Always use PATCH for updates, not PUT (partial updates are safer and more flexible).
- GET requests must be idempotent and safe (no side effects).
- DELETE requests must be idempotent (deleting twice returns same result).
- POST is not idempotent — creating twice creates two resources.

==============================
ENDPOINT PATTERNS
==============================

Standard CRUD for every resource:

Fairs:
  POST   /api/v1/fairs              — create fair
  GET    /api/v1/fairs              — list all fairs
  GET    /api/v1/fairs/:id          — get fair by ID (with customers)
  PATCH  /api/v1/fairs/:id          — update fair
  DELETE /api/v1/fairs/:id          — delete fair (cascade customers)

Customers (nested under fair for creation and listing):
  POST   /api/v1/fairs/:fairId/customers    — create customer in fair
  GET    /api/v1/fairs/:fairId/customers    — list customers of fair

Customers (standalone for update and delete):
  PATCH  /api/v1/customers/:id              — update customer
  DELETE /api/v1/customers/:id              — delete customer

Auth:
  POST   /api/v1/auth/login         — authenticate user
  POST   /api/v1/auth/register      — register new user
  POST   /api/v1/auth/refresh       — refresh access token
  POST   /api/v1/auth/logout        — invalidate refresh token

Users (admin only):
  GET    /api/v1/users              — list users
  GET    /api/v1/users/:id          — get user
  PATCH  /api/v1/users/:id          — update user
  DELETE /api/v1/users/:id          — delete user

Upload:
  POST   /api/v1/upload/card-image  — upload business card image

==============================
QUERY PARAMETERS
==============================

Filtering:
- Use field names as query params: ?conversionRate=high
- Multiple values: ?conversionRate=high,medium
- Example: GET /api/v1/fairs/:fairId/customers?conversionRate=high

Search:
- Use ?search= for text search across multiple fields.
- Backend searches name and company fields (case-insensitive).
- Example: GET /api/v1/fairs/:fairId/customers?search=acme

Sorting:
- Use ?sortBy= and ?sortOrder= params.
- sortOrder accepts: asc, desc (default: desc).
- Example: GET /api/v1/fairs?sortBy=startDate&sortOrder=desc
- Default sort: fairs by startDate desc, customers by createdAt desc.

Pagination:
- Use offset-based pagination: ?page= and ?limit=
- Default: page=1, limit=20
- Maximum limit: 100 (reject higher values)
- Response includes pagination metadata:
  {
    success: true,
    message: "...",
    data: [...],
    meta: {
      page: 1,
      limit: 20,
      total: 85,
      totalPages: 5
    }
  }

Combining:
- All query params can be combined:
  GET /api/v1/fairs/:fairId/customers?search=acme&conversionRate=high&page=1&limit=10&sortBy=createdAt&sortOrder=desc

==============================
RESPONSE FORMAT
==============================

All endpoints must return this standardized format:

Success (single resource):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Fair created successfully",
  "data": { ... }
}

Success (list):
{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Fairs retrieved successfully",
  "data": [ ... ],
  "meta": { "page": 1, "limit": 20, "total": 42, "totalPages": 3 }
}

Error:
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "Fair not found",
  "error": "NOT_FOUND"
}

Validation Error:
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "Validation failed",
  "error": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
  "details": [
    { "field": "name", "message": "Name is required" },
    { "field": "email", "message": "Invalid email format" }
  ]
}

==============================
HTTP STATUS CODES
==============================

Success:
  200 OK              — GET, PATCH, DELETE success
  201 Created          — POST success (resource created)

Client Errors:
  400 Bad Request      — validation error, malformed request
  401 Unauthorized     — missing or invalid authentication token
  403 Forbidden        — valid token but insufficient permissions (wrong role)
  404 Not Found        — resource does not exist
  409 Conflict         — duplicate resource (unique constraint violation)
  429 Too Many Requests — rate limit exceeded

Server Errors:
  500 Internal Server Error — unexpected server failure (never expose details)

Rules:
- Never return 200 for errors.
- Never return 500 for client errors.
- Always match the status code to the actual situation.

==============================
REQUEST BODY CONVENTIONS
==============================

- Use camelCase for all JSON field names: budgetRaw, conversionRate, startDate.
- Dates must be ISO 8601 format: "2025-03-15" or "2025-03-15T14:30:00.000Z".
- Enum values must match exactly: "very_high", "USD", "admin".
- Empty strings are treated as missing — validate accordingly.
- Arrays are sent as JSON arrays: "products": ["Kompresörler", "Vana Sistemleri"].

==============================
RESPONSE BODY CONVENTIONS
==============================

- Never return password or passwordHash fields.
- Always return id for every resource.
- Always return createdAt and updatedAt timestamps.
- Return related resources when appropriate (fair detail includes customers).
- Use null for absent optional fields, not undefined or empty string.
- Dates in responses are ISO 8601 strings.

==============================
AUTHENTICATION HEADERS
==============================

- Access token is sent in Authorization header:
  Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
- Refresh token is sent in request body to /auth/refresh.
- No tokens in URL query parameters — never.

==============================
IMPORTANT
==============================

- Every new endpoint must follow these patterns exactly.
- If a new resource type is added, follow the same CRUD pattern.
- Never create custom URL schemes that deviate from REST conventions.
- API must be stateless — no server-side sessions (JWT only).
- Design endpoints with future mobile app consumption in mind (Phase 2).
